body:
# Slack Webhooks

Incoming webhooks are the simplest way to post messages to Slack from external systems. A webhook URL is tied to a specific channel — send a JSON POST request and the message appears. No bot token or OAuth flow required.

## Setting Up Incoming Webhooks

1. Go to https://api.slack.com/apps and select (or create) your app
2. Navigate to **Incoming Webhooks** and toggle it on
3. Click **Add New Webhook to Workspace**
4. Select the target channel and authorize
5. Copy the webhook URL (format: `https://hooks.slack.com/services/T.../B.../xxx`)

Store the webhook URL in an environment variable. Never commit it to source — anyone with the URL can post to your channel.

## Sending a Message

```javascript
const webhookUrl = process.env.SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL;

const response = await fetch(webhookUrl, {
  method: "POST",
  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
  body: JSON.stringify({
    text: "Deployment complete! :rocket:"
  })
});
```

Or use the `@slack/webhook` package for a typed client:

```javascript
import { IncomingWebhook } from "@slack/webhook";

const webhook = new IncomingWebhook(process.env.SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL);

await webhook.send({
  text: "Deployment complete! :rocket:",
  blocks: [
    {
      type: "section",
      text: {
        type: "mrkdwn",
        text: "*Deployment complete* :rocket:\nService `api-gateway` deployed to production."
      }
    },
    {
      type: "context",
      elements: [
        { type: "mrkdwn", text: "Deployed by CI/CD pipeline | <https://github.com/org/repo/actions|View logs>" }
      ]
    }
  ]
});
```

## Formatting

Webhooks support the same formatting as regular messages:

- **Plain text** — set `text` for simple messages
- **Mrkdwn** — use Slack's `mrkdwn` syntax for `*bold*`, `_italic_`, `~strike~`, and links `<url|text>`
- **Block Kit** — include a `blocks` array for rich layouts (see [[slack/block-kit]])
- **Username and icon** — override with `username` and `icon_emoji` or `icon_url`

```javascript
await webhook.send({
  username: "Deploy Bot",
  icon_emoji: ":robot_face:",
  text: "Build #42 passed",
  blocks: [
    {
      type: "header",
      text: { type: "plain_text", text: "Build #42 Passed" }
    },
    { type: "divider" },
    {
      type: "section",
      fields: [
        { type: "mrkdwn", text: "*Branch:*\nmain" },
        { type: "mrkdwn", text: "*Duration:*\n3m 42s" },
        { type: "mrkdwn", text: "*Commit:*\n`a1b2c3d`" },
        { type: "mrkdwn", text: "*Author:*\n<@U0123456>" }
      ]
    }
  ]
});
```

## Best Practices

- **Rate limiting** — Slack allows ~1 message per second per webhook. Batch or queue for higher volumes.
- **Fallback text** — Always include `text` even when using `blocks` for notification previews and accessibility.
- **Error handling** — Webhook POST returns `ok` (200) on success, or an error string. Check the response body.
- **Security** — Treat webhook URLs as secrets. Rotate them if compromised by revoking and re-creating.
- **Channel changes** — To post to a different channel, create a new webhook. Each URL is bound to one channel.
- **Limitations** — Webhooks are one-way (send only). For receiving messages or interactions, use [[slack/bots]] or [[slack/events]].
